items.title: Cicadellidae spp.
items.content_text: Small planthopper on Poa labillardieri, four seen on the same plant, all of them hopped away before I could get close enough for a better photo or photos from other angles

items.title: Scrobiger splendidus
items.content_text: Constantly on the move, head often buried deep into the flowers, flying around every now and then as well. Scrobiger sp., maybe Scrobiger splendidus??

items.title: Pompilidae spp.
items.content_text: Mostly foraging through the flowers, although it also spent some time amongst the foliage. My third visit in two days to the same flowering tree which is attracting a lot of insects! The orange wings make me think Cryptocheilus sp.

items.title: Abispa spp.

Looks like Abispa ephippium http://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:4901340b-3412-4dc1-95c9-75e298fede63#overview

Moved about quickly, very difficult to get any photos!

items.title: Eurymeloides punctata
items.content_text: Edit: I originally had these as Eurymeloides pulchra, as there were a few adult E. pulchra nearby, but I have been informed via Facebook when I shared this image that these are Eurymeloides punctata. I have compared with E. pulchra that I photographed here https://natureshare.org.au/observations/583d4f24ed2a897480005e60?species=Eurymeloides+pulchra and also images found online - the early instars are similar but E. punctata appear darker and brighter with slightly different markings as shown in this photo and e.g. here http://www.brisbaneinsects.com/brisbane_planthoppers/PunctataHoppe.htm and here https://sites.google.com/site/insectsoftasmaniahemiptera/suborder-auchenorrhyncha/cicadellidae-leafhoppers/genus-eurymeloides/eurymeloides-punctata
